  <Subject Subject_ID="300056476">
    <Parent_Relationships>
      <Preferred_Parent>
        <Parent_Subject_ID>300056462</Parent_Subject_ID>
        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>art genres [300056462], genres in the visual arts [300056444], concepts in the arts and humanities [300056107], Associated Concepts (hierarchy name) [300055126], Associated Concepts Facet [300264086]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Includes art undertaken in conjunction with particular communities, often socially deprived, usually with the idea of producing an effect or inspiring response specifically within those communities, with no reference to widely established standards. For art intended to beautify and enrich public places, use "public art."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Incluye el arte abordado en conjunción con comunidades particulares, a menudo socialmente deprimidos, usualmente con la idea de producir un efecto o respuesta inspiradora específicamente dentro de aquellas comunidades, sin referencia a patrones ampliamente establecidos. Para el arte que pretende embellecer y mejorar espacios públicos, use "arte público".</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Omvat kunst ondernomen in samenwerking met specifieke bevolkingsgroepen, vaak sociaal achtergesteld, meestal met de bedoeling om juist bij deze bevolkingsgroepen effect te sorteren of respons uit te lokken, zonder referentie naar alom gevestigde maatstaven. Gebruik 'openbare kunst' voor kunst bedoeld om openbare gebouwen, enz. op te fleuren en te verrijken.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099099/Van Dale groot woordenboek (1994)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>通常在社會上較為弱勢的特定社區協力進行的藝術，主要概念是希望在社區中引發效應或引起迴響，並沒有既定的標準。至於用來美化或豐富公共場所的藝術，則稱之為「公共藝術」。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Inclui arte realizada em conjunto com comunidades específicas, muitas vezes socialmente desfavorecidas, geralmente com a ideia de produzir um efeito ou uma resposta inspiradora especificamente nessas comunidades, sem qualquer referência a padrões amplamente estabelecidos. Para arte destinada a embelezar e enriquecer locais públicos, use “arte pública”.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109633/CVAA-BR Consortium (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
